d librarians as well as charlatans, hucksters, profiteers, and rabble-rousers—all whose lives reflect changes in modern Buddhism even as they themselves shape the course of these changes. The editors and contributors are fundamentally concerned with how individual Buddhists make meaning and display this understanding to others. Some practitioners profiled look to the past, lamenting the transformations Buddhism has undergone in recent times, while others embrace these. Some have adopted a “new asceticism,” while others are eager to explore different religious traditions as they think about their own ways of being Buddhist. Arranging the profiles according to these themes—looking backward, forward, inward, and outward—reveals the value of studying individual Buddhists and their idiosyncratic religious backgrounds and attitudes, thus highlighting the diversity of approaches to the practice and study of Buddhism in Asia today. Students and teachers will welcome sections on further readings and additional tables of contents that organize the profiles thematically, as well as by tradition (Theravada, Mahayana, Vajrayana), region, and country.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aBuddhism and culturezAsia. 0aBuddhismzAsia. 0aBuddhistszAsiavBiography. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / General (see also PHILOSOPHY / Buddhist).2bisacsh1 a(Ruiz), Roger Casas.1 aBaird, Ian G.1 aBaird, Ian G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Corey L.1 aBell, Corey L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerkwitz, Stephen C.1 aBerkwitz, Stephen C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, Anya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, Anya.1 aBhutia, Kalzang Dorjee, econtributor.4ctb4https:/